Right here you have the Solid Waste Disposal Act of 1965, as well as the Texas Health and Safety Code, and of course, the city code and ordinances. You're all familiar with the forward facing departments that we have or forward facing business units that we have. Next slide. Okay, just a functional review of our organizational chart. You'll see where basically we have three different sections in the department. But as you can see, the estimated total for this FY 23 year will be about $95.6 million. All right, next slide, please. At this point, I'd like to turn this point of the presentation over to our CFO, Ms. Wealthy White. Thank you, Director. The solid waste department revenues are generated through two funds the general fund and the recycling revenue fund. The General Fund revenues includes fees from our dumpster permits, our extra capacity container program, our nonresidential garbage and our container lease fee and some other small accounts. The Recycling Revenue Fund is generated from the sale of recyclable materials like glass, scrap metal, batteries, electronics which are sold by the City. Also included in this fund are fees from our tire recycling and our business recycling programs. On this slide, we see a projected 3% increase in General Fund revenues due to the annual CPI and prior year revenue activity to be realized in fiscal year 2023. There is no projected increase in the Recycling Revenue Fund, and with these revenue funds, we have a total budget revenue budget of $14.8 million. Next slide, please. Our expenditures by funds are our department, our collection programs and other service delivery components. Includes our garbage collection, tree waste, heavy trash depositories, curbside recycling, drive through recycling facilities, sponsorships. All these areas are supported by the General Fund. And the fiscal year 2023 proposed budget is $95.6 million, which represents a 1% increase from the current fiscal year. The Recycling Revenue Fund proposed expenditure supports the City's recycling programs, related services and recycling education. The proposed budget for fiscal year 2023 is $4.1 million and it represents a 5% increase from fiscal year 2022. Next slide, please. Looking at go ahead. Yeah, they're ahead. You can go ahead and explain if you can back up one slide to the pie chart. Thank you. The projected budget by fund for fiscal year 2023 in the General Fund budget, personnel represents 41% of the total budget. nonpersonal accounts for 59% of the proposed budget, and within that 59% services are 23%. And restricted accounts, supplies, non, capital transfer and debt make up the balance of 36%. In the Recycling Revenue Fund, the percentage for personnel is ten point 57 and nonpersonal is 89%. The next slide shows the net change in the General Fund. Next slide, please. Thank you. At the start of fiscal year 2022, the Solid Waste Management Department began with a budget of $89 million and with adjustments throughout the year, it increased the budget to 95, 601, 576. Looking forward to the fiscal year 2023 General Fund budget. Additional adjustments were made to include contractual and mandated adjustments resulting in a proposed budget of $95,610,939, which is again a net change of approximately 1% from the current year's budget. Next slide. All right. Thank you, Ms. White. Now with this FY 23 proposed budget, we do expect some impacts and a lot of those impacts are going to come just by growth and demand, increasing growth in demand throughout the city. We also expect some of those impacts to be attributed to the vacancy rates that we currently have that we're working on driving down overtime, as well as temporary services that we'll use to mitigate some of the shortfalls that we incur throughout the year. Operational program subsidies will be another area that we think will also impact. And that's just from observation of being here a little more than six months. Meaning that we may at times have some a need to supplement our services by calling in help from some of our private counterparts in the industry that will be in the areas of heavy trash collection which we're about to embark upon right now, as well as curbside recycling. And then again, we have challenges with addressing some of the neighborhood density projects that are going on and some of the inflationary contracts that we're seeing or inflationary impact to contracts that we're seeing today. Next slide. Okay, again, FY 22 accomplishments. There have been several that have been going on prior to my arrival and then since my arrival, they've continued to keep the momentum going. I think the biggest takeaway throughout the year has been the fact that the city has gotten aggressive and they recognize the fact that we've had a shortage in some of our key or critical positions, that being the driving positions. And the $3,000 sign in bonus was great for a while, but now we're recognizing the fact that everybody else has gotten hip to the game. So we've got to continuously think of something new and innovative to recruit and attract more talent. So Mayor Turner actually, and as well as some of the council members here, have been instrumental in kind of helping us develop CDL training programs that we're currently working on right now. And then we're also actively, still actively recruiting licensed CDL drivers, but we've also got a pay increase on the way for them as well. So hopefully that will continue to attract more qualified talent in this area. Next slide. Some of the FY 23 goals. Again I think the biggest goal that we have that you'll hear me constantly say is we want to reduce our dependency on the general fund. Meaning that we want to become a more sustainable department in the way that we, we manage our department, the way that we manage our resources and again become more solvent in that process. We want to diversify the revenue streams I know there's a lot of talk about the city of Houston not having a residential rate and then that is the case too. We would love to continue working on that and there's some other opportunities as well to diversify the revenue streams as well as it involves working in the commercial sector or offering our services to some of the commercial programs that may be out there throughout the city. We also plan to reduce our vacancy rate. We're currently hovering around 17% right now, department wide, maybe about 15% for our critical vacancies. Again, working with Mayor Turner, adjusting the starting salary that should be taking place within the next couple of days. We noticed that we think we'll be a little bit more competitive with our counterparts in the private industry and get our starting rate up closer to $22, $23 an hour. And then we really want to work on standardizing our routes too. And a lot of this has to do with the growth. And that's a good thing. The growth that the city of Houston has incurred over the last decade. And it's time for the solid waste department to catch up with that growth right now so that we can continue our quest and accomplish our goals as far as delivering on time services concerned. Next slide. It's just a little graph and some studies that we've been doing again with the long cities or the department's long range plan that's been out there. Just a couple of facts over the last ten years. I believe we see now the population of the city of Houston being about 6.6 million. To us, that represents about 20,000 additional households that we're still servicing with the same level of organizational support that we had ten years ago. And again about a 300 or 225 ton increase on a daily basis that we're still responsible for collecting. So we definitely feel the strain. Now the bottom, the other arrows may seem a little bit confusing because we have it pointing down, but it says 2% increase. The reason I did that is because again, the city has grown exponentially in those ten years and the department has not kept up with that growth and that's why we're experiencing such challenges with service delays, probably a less than a 1% increase and no increase in the size of the fleet. You'll hear me constantly say we got to invest in our greatest assets, employees and equipment. Without those two, we can't deliver that service. Next slide. I'm sorry, can you hold that slide for a second? The top of the chart, the line graph, just kind of illustrates that relationship that you have. Most cities our size has when it comes down to full time employees, to number of households served. And you'll see the blue line, which represents our FTEs, normally should be above that orange line. As far as households serve, you want to keep that relationship. Houston is at the end. You see there's a big disparity there when it comes down to our counterparts. Next slide. And that concludes our presentation. Happy to answer any questions that anyone may have. Thank you, Director. First question comes from Council member Abby Cayman. Thanks, Chair. First Director. Thank you. And please relay our appreciation to everyone in the department, especially our drivers that are out in the field. Are they still working six days a week right now? Yes, we're still at six days a week, hopefully not much longer. Yeah, and I know I've seen some drivers out there. We all work late, but not as late as they do. We're not up as early as they are. So please relay my gratitude to them really quickly. I wanted to check in because we talked about the increase in multifamily and looking at additional needs towards the future. I had passed, with the support of council last fiscal year, a budget amendment that was going to direct the department by the end of fiscal year 22 to start the stakeholder engagement process. So we can be looking at mandatory multifamily recycling, whether the city takes on that burden or not, just requires private, but where are we in that process and has that begun yet? Yes, and that's a good question. I'm happy to report that process is going, it is ongoing. I believe the team started that prior to my arrival and since then, now we are to the point where we are meeting biweekly and when I say we, I'm talking about members of the Apartment Association and other industrial and commercial businesses throughout town that represents those areas. Perfect, because as we talk about future needs, and I know many of us around the Horseshoe bring this up as to you, the life cycle of our landfills and if we do not start curbing waste now, we're going to be in big trouble. So I thank you for that update. And in terms of the profitability of recycling materials right now, are we seeing an improvement in that? Yes, there's been a slight improvement in there. I think our CFO can attest to that as well. In fact, I don't believe we have to pay our processor now. Is that correct? Yeah. So the way our contract is set up is that when the materials, the blended value of the materials reaches a certain threshold that the city doesn't have to pay. Right. And just one follow up on that and then I'll go back in the queue. There was an effort to educate on the contamination of recyclable materials. Are we seeing an improvement in that? Yes, we are. And we're currently working with our processor right now to find out what that new rate is. When I arrived, I believe our contamination rate was around 39%. We're going to be doing another evaluation within the next couple of weeks, in the next week or two, and we expect that rate to be down. Terrific. We're already seeing indications fantastic. And if I could go back in queue, please make sure council Member Amy Pick. Thank you, Mayor Pertem. And thank you, Director. First, I want to thank you for the work that you're doing, especially in District Day. We've seen a huge improvement in collections since you've been on board. And when we were meeting about using our service funds to supplement the work, your question was you weren't just, of course we'll take your money. You were really questioning, well, why are we not picking it up on time? And I really appreciated how you were thinking about that. So my question is about the business recycling program and the commercial collections. Have those two programs been evaluated recently to see if it's beneficial to continue that financially or if that's something we should suspend or increase or has that been evaluated? Yes, and we're currently working with some partners here. When I say partners, I mean these are big partners, ExxonMobil and whatnot. So we have the small scale recycling, commercial recycling program for the small producers and small businesses. And that seems to be working relatively well right now. We know that there are some opportunities for improvement, and we're working on addressing that right now. But perhaps I think the biggest takeaway is that a lot of the partners that want to work with us right now, they see the value in that program. They appreciate the fact that we've gotten started and they're ready to help us take it to the next level. So abandoning it would not be the right choice at this time. And as far as the commercial collections for trash pickup, is that something that has been evaluated, too, where commercial businesses can basically contract with the city for a pickup? That's something that I'm evaluating right now. I still need to spend some time with our revenue and finance team, but I do see some serious potentials in there. Okay, thank you. We can't keep giving away the business. Council Member Sally Alcorn. Thank you, Chair, and thank you, director, for your presentation. You're operating according to the solid waste, long range solid waste plan at a $20 to $40 million deficit. Correct. Just walking in the door. $20 to $40 million down, we're picking up 391,000 homes. Correct. We've got another 50,000 on sponsorship that are paying their own private trash. Correct. I really appreciated your slide that had the different cities on there. I would add that those cities that you have on those slides, especially Dallas, San Antonio and Austin, all have a fee. The fee in Dallas is $34.30. Weekly garbage and recycling, monthly brush and bulky bulk waste. Austin has pay as you throw ranges from twenty two dollars and sixty five cents to forty nine dollars and fifty cents a month. San Antonio, $14 through they also have pays. You throw through $26. It's employees and it's equipment. And I don't see how you get there with $96 million a year from the general fund. So I'd like you to give me your experience in Tampa and any other experience you have with how a fee was originated and how you think that might play out here. Absolutely, sure. In Tampa, as well as other enterprise fund departments in the solid waste industry, fee was a little bit higher in Tamps, around $36 per household. But that fee was also covering the cost of the service. So employees and equipment first supplies the other associated expenses that come along with managing a solid waste program. People often forget about the true cost of disposal. Those are real dollars. So when we show up at a disposal facility at a landfill and we have to drive across someone's scales, there's no sort of internal fund transfer that satisfies that transaction. There's a check that they're looking for and that disposal cost usually cost about a third of the service. And if I was going to rank it, I would probably rank it somewhere between number one and three. When it comes down to the assets, it's going to be right there. Between the cost of employees and the cost of equipment are the three greatest costs of that service. So again, that's what your rate is designed to cover. In Tampa, we also had a different disposal system, so we had a bond to cover. So our rate was designed to cover the cost of satisfying the bond each year. However, once we reached the areas and the bonds matured and we paid that bond off, we enjoyed a $14 million swing. Really, it's about a $28 million swing. All of that money did not stay in the department. We can't show a profit. We cover our reserves, rainy day funds and whatnot. The rest of that has to go back to the general fund in order to support other areas of the city. So whenever you hear me talk about a rate or bringing on a rate, it's number one to take care of what we need to take care of in house so that we can deliver the on time service and have the equipment that we need so that our men and women can show up and deliver that and not have to stay out until eight or 09:00 at night or come in on a Sunday. But it's to cover that first and then support the other areas of the city that need it second. And when you talk about the city of Houston, we got a lot of work to do, right. So if we were to embark upon that road, it's going to be a couple of years before we start seeing the benefits of that return. But the goal would be, again, as I mentioned earlier, to reduce our dependency on the general fund and allow those funds to be used for other areas throughout the city. I told Council Member Pat I was offended when she sat across from me and said that she wanted to run her solid waste programs like, well, what are we? And I know Houston has gotten away with it, but I think with the times and conditions and the way things are today, we've got to find some way to offset that, and I think our residents and customers deserve better. Right. And so if you could address that, I'd appreciate it. Absolutely. And I think what we may be seeing is it may speak to trying to find the right way to say this, the difference in neighborhoods throughout the city of Houston, as large as it is. In other districts. They may have a few more commercial areas than residential areas, so their approach may be a little bit different. It may be a quarterly approach or something of that nature. But what we're seeing and what I'm observing is that each district has its own unique features, and one district may require a hot team. And we appreciate the hot teams because they kind of fill in the gap right now where we want to, but we just can't because we're trying to address the more pressing issues. And I think that's why you may see that from as I travel throughout and I look at some of the neighborhoods and I see where there is a greater need for some of those areas. And I think the wonderful thing that I've learned about City of Houston, I was kind of kicking myself because I wish I would have met with them on the first day that I was here is the Mayor's Office of Innovation and Sustainability. They've got some wonderful ideas. And we were chatting the other day about now that we know where a majority of our debris is being generated at what kind of programs, how can we augment our programs so that we can concentrate our equipment in those areas and not as heavy on the areas where there is not as much generation of the illegal dumping and whatnot? And I think that's why a lot of times you'll see that difference. Right. I do understand that it's a difference, but we had talked about it, and I didn't know if you were able to do that, which we talked about, but apparently not at this juncture, not at this time. Would it be pay for additional equipment? Like, where would that money go towards? Right. Wilfred, I must say, you've done a bang up job in your initial time here. I used to always tell everybody, I love me some Harry Hayes. I'll always love me some Harry Hayes. But you've done a great job coming in and picking up what Harry Hayes started developing. I hate to see Mr. Anthony Bowie retiring. And I see Ms. Carolyn out there. Is there any option for us here in the city to do something similar to what you did in Tampa? I would love it. So, idea wise, how much does it cost? Today, you're probably looking at about a billion dollars. Yeah. The last one that I know of that was permitted in South Florida was about 880,000,000. Is there any coming back in that market I haven't really looked at? Yeah, it's kind of leveled out, but we're still not seeing what you all enjoyed during that time ago. In fact, from Florida, I used to look at that and I used to catch heat because people would say, how come you're not doing what Texas is doing? But again, it's a regional market. It's very volatile. I definitely wouldn't bet my life savings on it. But right now, we're kind of breaking even in that recycling market as far as the commodities are concerned. Thank you, Director Bowie. We'll miss you. You've done a great job for us, for you. And so have you, director Wright. Even though you're not going anywhere, we're not letting you. Council member Robert Gallegos. Thank you, Mayor Pro TEM. Thank you, Director, for the presentation. It was enjoyed visiting with you last week in regards to getting some updates, I know that leaving my office right now. Constituent services pointed out to me that we have a constituent that has been waiting for a trash can, because I believe their trash can was stolen, and they've been waiting for a. Trash can since April. I know that we have some trash cans that are sitting on Capitol Street that they're still been waiting for that trash to be picked up. If we're leaning towards a fee, we need to let the public know why. So if you can elaborate what the issues are, please. Yeah, and there's several compounding issues and I think we also want to be clear to say that the fee gets us going in the right direction. It's not the magic elixir. So what people may be experiencing when they run into those delays is, again, we're dealing with 420 some odd employees department wide. That's not enough. 645 sq mi. 645 sq mi. Exactly. So what you see the team doing is concentrating on the big fires and trying to keep those from growing even larger. So if somebody's waiting on a can, it could very well be because another team member was reassigned to take care of a route and that may have been more pressing that day. We have some systems that we also have to kind of update and how we as it pertains to logistics and maybe service order management to kind of make that a little bit more electronic than manual. So that's part of the growth and development opportunities that we have in the department that we haven't been able to take advantage of. And again, you mentioned earlier about the vehicles. Some of the vehicles in our fleet are as old as minimum ten years old. And the average life of a garbage truck should be around five to seven years. You should be replacing them. So we've got to get that vehicle replacement program up to where it should be so that once we know that five to seven year mark is there, we're looking at trying to replace that. So the model that the team has generated that seems to be effective right now. They're always going to concentrate on garbage first. We don't want that to sit out for days and whatnot and draw the flies and vectors that come along with that. And then we'll make up the recycling a little bit later during the week. So just a snapshot of the delay. And what I've stated to your predecessor, Director Hayes, when he brought this to my attention years ago, that we were needing a garbage fee because all these other major cities in the state of Texas have a monthly garbage fee. What I stated as when I was president of my civic club and president of the super neighborhood. It's also going to be to pick up those tires that are being dumped on the vacant lot. It's also to be pick up that illegal dumping, that's being dumped in the neighborhood, that's bringing down our neighborhood, that's causing crime because of all this illegal dumping. So it's a catch 22 and we pay a monthly garbage fee. Constituents are going to expect more than just picking up the trash can and your recycling bin. And that's what I'm hoping will happen is that we'll be able to pick up those tires while I'm able to pick up the illegal dumping and clean up our neighborhoods at the same time. And I think the majority of the public will go with it. Exactly. Just to add on to that, again, there are some opportunities to create some more programs that concentrate on solid waste. And I know we have code enforcement officers and we work with our neighborhood department with that. But in order to address the issues that we have now, I really feel that there would be some benefits for the solid waste department to have its own code enforcement team, maybe two or three for each sector. And as we see these illegal dumping issues pop up, it gives us an opportunity to concentrate the time that's needed on mitigating the issues. And I know you brought that up to me when we met. And I totally agree that there needs to be code enforcement inspectors inside of waste so that those that end up putting their illegal dumping out a day or two after it was already picked up in the neighborhood, they can be told you're not supposed to do this. Give them a warning and hopefully they will stop doing that in that way of cleaning up our neighborhoods. Council Member David Robinson. If you have anything to add to that, I'd love to hear it. Thank you. Council Member Robinson I don't want that billion dollars to scare you, right? It's a big number. But you got to look at the value of that beyond the dollars and cents.
